item.title: Trump vows to use military, police shot
item.description: At least five US police officers have been hit by gunfire during violent protests over the death of a black man in police custody, hours after President Donald Trump vowed to use the military to halt the unrest.

item.title: WA man had photos of girls bound, gagged
item.description: A man caught with sexual images of young children, including some who were bound, gagged and obviously distressed, has been sentenced to 14 months in a Western Australian prison.

item.title: Autopsies clash on cause of Floyd’s death
item.description: A medical examiner's office has ruled that the death of George Floyd, the black man whose killing in Minneapolis police custody last week triggered nationwide protests, was a homicide and that he died from asphyxiation.

item.title: Florida suspends officer for pushing woman
item.description: Fort Lauderdale police have suspended an officer after video showed he pushed a kneeling black woman to the ground during protests, escalating a clash where bottles were thrown and tear gas was fired.

item.title: Obama urges US criminal justice reform
item.description: Former US president Barack Obama has penned a lengthy essay urging his country to "get to work" to enact criminal justice reform and address systemic racism after a weekend of protests over the death of George Floyd at the hands of Minneapolis police.

item.title: Swedish PM to appoint coronavirus inquiry
item.description: Sweden will launch an inquiry into the country's handling of the pandemic before the northern summer, Prime Minister Stefan Lofven has said in a newspaper interview amid growing criticism over nursing home deaths and the lack of testing.

item.title: French COVID-19 cases in hospitals dip
item.description: The French health ministry says people should continue taking protective measures against the coronavirus even as cases in hospitals and intensive care continue to fall.

item.title: UK contact-tracing going well, govt says
item.description: Britain's coronavirus test-and-trace system is working well and some of the thousands of contact-tracers who have been recruited are not yet fully occupied, Health Secretary Matt Hancock says.

item.title: Spain reports no daily coronavirus death
item.description: Spain says it's reporting no deaths in a 24-hour period from the coronavirus for the first time since March.

item.title: Iran MP says 230 killed in November unrest
item.description: An Iranian MP says 230 people were killed in November's anti-government protests in Iran, the official news agency reports.
